SW,<br><br>
Thought provoking question!  Obviously, I can only answer for myself, and my actions.  I served in Cu Chi, not the Ashau (sp) Valley.  I left in December of 1967 and I felt guilt back in New Jersey when Tet of 68 swept through Vietnam.<br><br>
I can't judge anyone but myself, nor would I want to judge anyone else.  To me that is unethical.  I wouldn't know where or how to begin.  I can't see what is in or what was in anyone else's mind or heart.  I go back to that oft quoted phrase THERE BUT FOR THE GRACE OF GOD GO I.  Life is tough enough for many people without me throwing my opinions at them.<br><br>
Vietnam &quot;made us&quot; ask hard questions of ourselves, whether we went or not.  How well we asked ourselves those questions depends is (should be) a private matter.<br><br>
The mother of a good friend of mine once said &quot;don't knock denial if you haven't tried it.&quot;  I couldn't argue with her.<br><br>
Paul
